ing Jetty APIs. The classes like Server, ServerConnector, and HTTP2CServerConnectionFactory will be useful here. I should ensure no extra dependencies are needed for the Jakarta servlet API in Jetty 11. Testing possibilities include exposing factory configurations and making HTTP/2 requests like GET /hello.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Parsing server settings**\\n\\nI need to parse server settings, focusing on aspects like WINDOW_UPDATE, response HEADERS, and DATA. It’s important to ensure the stream ends correctly, as this could affect multiple points in the process. I’m considering a POST request for content, which will involve managing data handling and ensuring the server reads the body appropriately. This could be a bit of a juggling act, but I'm keen to get all the details sorted out properly!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_qP5dHsthf9Zly3pOAg5w3IdC|fc_038be03ba358fe9a016a025dfaebf481a3afd8db54f2166eda", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.eclipse.jetty.http2/http2-server/11.0.24/build/reports/dynamic-access/dynamic-access-coverage.json", "limit": 200}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 3058, "output": 651, "cacheRead": 24576, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 28285, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778540014220, "responseId": "resp_038be03ba358fe9a016a025deedfe881a3b38742aaeda88beb"}}
