[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Testing HTTP/2 server**\n\nI’m considering how to test an HTTP/2 server. I might write integration tests with a Jetty server and JDK HttpClient, but I’m wondering about h2c support. It seems the Java 11 client can handle HTTP/2 over TLS, and h2c might not be an option. Jetty’s http2-client could work without adding extra dependencies. I’ll also look into using raw sockets to send HTTP/2 frames directly, which could help with understanding the connection and parser better.\n\n**Planning HTTP/2 integration test**\n\nFor integration testing, I think using Java Socket to send preface bytes and basic frames is the easiest route. I’ll need to generate HEADERS with HpackEncoder, as the existing tests are using it. I could manually write the HTTP/2 frame bytes and then parse the response frames using HpackDecoder. \n\nNext, I need to build a server using Jetty APIs. The classes like Server, ServerConnector, and HTTP2CServerConnectionFactory will be useful here. I should ensure no extra dependencies are needed for the Jakarta servlet API in Jetty 11. Testing possibilities include exposing factory configurations and making HTTP/2 requests like GET /hello.\n\n**Parsing server settings**\n\nI need to parse server settings, focusing on aspects like WINDOW_UPDATE, response HEADERS, and DATA. It’s important to ensure the stream ends correctly, as this could affect multiple points in the process. I’m considering a POST request for content, which will involve managing data handling and ensuring the server reads the body appropriately. This could be a bit of a juggling act, but I'm keen to get all the details sorted out properly!", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_038be03ba358fe9a016a025def918c81a3a43f5a91d793bfd2\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqAl36xZPO7UkVeVcY8xBBs1CenLpo7gK5i3e73HkJ2q119OjLqzGofE4TclZnwDK4O3SasMyKG94l62A05le1exYrzMmCD6lHCTuIBEZvgo